#: Game.Levels.MeetFin.L11_ProofIrrelevance
msgid "This property is called **proof irrelevance**: the identity of a\n"
"آ§0 element depends only on its value, not on which proof\n"
"witnesses the bound. This is a direct consequence of the eta\n"
"principle (آ§1 / آ§2 from Levels 9â€“10): since an\n"
"element is determined by its value, two elements with the same\n"
"value must be equal â€” regardless of how their bound proofs were\n"
"obtained.\n"
"\n"
"Notice the proof pattern: آ§3 then آ§4. This\n"
"two-step combo â€” **reduce to values, then compute** â€” is the\n"
"standard way to prove آ§5 equalities when the values can be\n"
"determined from hypotheses. We'll call this the **Fin equality\n"
"pattern**: آ§6. You'll use it frequently.\n"
"\n"
"The deeper reason this works is that **آ§7 is proof-irrelevant\n"
"in Lean**: any two proofs of the same proposition are considered\n"
"equal. So آ§8 and آ§9 â€” no matter how they\n"
"were obtained â€” are the same proof. This means آ§10\n"
"automatically, and equality of آ§11 elements reduces to equality\n"
"of values.\n"
"\n"
"This isn't special to آ§12 â€” it applies to **every subtype** in Lean.\n"
"Any type of the form آ§13 (a value bundled with a\n"
"proof) has the same property: two elements are equal when their values\n"
"are equal, regardless of the proofs. The same آ§14\n"
"pattern works for any subtype where the predicate involves arithmetic.\n"
"You'll meet other subtypes later (like آ§15), and\n"
"proof irrelevance will apply there too."
